PLYR-Qt vendoring patch for ripser.cpp
=======================================

This documents the minimal, surgical edits applied to upstream
ripser.cpp (Ulrich Bauer, MIT) so the file can be statically linked
as a library into plyr_qt instead of running as a stand-alone CLI.
The upstream source is otherwise untouched; in particular the
persistence-homology algorithm itself is unchanged.

Three compile-time knobs were introduced, all off by default so the
original ripser.cpp still builds unchanged with a plain
`g++ ripser.cpp -o ripser`:

  -DRIPSER_NO_MAIN          Fences the CLI driver (`main()`, the
                            file-format readers, `print_usage_and_exit`,
                            and the `enum file_format`). When set, the
                            translation unit exports only the templated
                            `ripser<>` class and its supporting types
                            (plus the trampoline below if enabled).

  -DRIPSER_USE_OUTPUT_HOOK  Redirects the per-pair `std::cout` output
                            that ripser produces under
                            `PRINT_PERSISTENCE_PAIRS` to two extern
                            functions the caller supplies:

                                void ripser_begin_dim(int dim);
                                void ripser_emit_pair(int dim,
                                                      value_t birth,
                                                      value_t death);

                            `death` is +infinity for an unkillable
                            feature (the eternal connected component,
                            or any H>=1 feature that survives the
                            filtration threshold).

  -DRIPSER_PLYR_QT_TRAMPOLINE  Appends one extern-"C" function at
                            the bottom of the TU:

                                void phRunRipser(const float* lowerDistances,
                                                 int n,
                                                 float threshold,
                                                 int dimMax);

                            This is the only entry point downstream
                            code calls. It move-constructs a
                            compressed_lower_distance_matrix from the
                            flat input array and runs Ripser at
                            ratio=1.0, modulus=2, Z/2Z coefficients.

Edit summary (unified-diff style hunks, not literal `diff -u`):

* Near the top of the file (after `typedef coefficient_t`), declared
  the two extern hook functions inside
  `#if defined(RIPSER_USE_OUTPUT_HOOK)`.

* Added `#include <limits>` to the standard-header block (used by the
  `std::numeric_limits<value_t>::infinity()` call we emit for
  unkillable features).

* Each `std::cout` site under `PRINT_PERSISTENCE_PAIRS` (there are
  six: two `ripser_begin_dim` headers and four pair emits) was wrapped
  in an `#ifdef RIPSER_USE_OUTPUT_HOOK ... #else <original cout>
  #endif` block, so the original CLI path is byte-identical when the
  hook macro is undefined.

* The CLI driver block — `enum file_format` through the end of
  `int main(int argc, char** argv)` — was wrapped in
  `#ifndef RIPSER_NO_MAIN ... #endif`.

* A new section was appended at the very bottom of the file, behind
  `#if defined(RIPSER_PLYR_QT_TRAMPOLINE)`, defining the extern-"C"
  trampoline `phRunRipser`. It move-constructs a
  compressed_lower_distance_matrix from the caller's flat
  lower-triangular array and invokes ripser<...>::compute_barcodes()
  at ratio=1.0, modulus=2.

* Removed the `static` qualifier from four function-local
  enumerator caches inside `class ripser<>`:

    get_zero_pivot_facet:     static simplex_boundary_enumerator   facets(0, *this);
    get_zero_pivot_cofacet:   static simplex_coboundary_enumerator cofacets(*this);
    init_coboundary_and_get_pivot: static simplex_coboundary_enumerator cofacets(*this);
    add_simplex_coboundary:   static simplex_coboundary_enumerator cofacets(*this);

  These statics held a reference (`const ripser& parent`) to *this.
  In the original CLI they're harmless because the process runs
  exactly one Ripser computation in its lifetime. In our use we
  invoke Ripser many times per session on independent instances --
  the second instance's compute_barcodes() then dereferences a
  freed `parent` (use-after-free, crashes nondeterministically).
  This patch is unconditional rather than gated, because the
  upstream CLI still constructs/destructs each enumerator exactly
  once (cost is a couple-dozen-bytes of stack per construction).

Build invocation (CMakeLists.txt):

    add_library(ripser STATIC third_party/ripser/ripser.cpp)
    target_compile_definitions(ripser PUBLIC
        RIPSER_NO_MAIN
        RIPSER_USE_OUTPUT_HOOK
        RIPSER_PLYR_QT_TRAMPOLINE)

Caller responsibility: provide ripser_begin_dim / ripser_emit_pair
in some translation unit linked alongside ripser.cpp. PLYR-Qt does
this in src/PersistentHomologyAnalyzer.cpp.

The patch is reversible: each edit is bracketed and selectable by
toggling the two compile-time knobs.
